\pard\f0\fs28    ({\b a}) Subsp. {\b scoparius}: Branches erect or ascending, 150-200(-250) cm; leaves and young twigs glabrous or sparsely sericeous. 2n = 46. {\i Woods, heaths, dunes and mountain slopes; usually calcifuge. Throughout the range of the species}.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28    ({\b b}) Subsp. {\b maritimus} (Rouy) Heywood,{\i  Proc. Bot. Soc. Brit. Is.}{\b  3}: 176 (1959) ({\i Genista scoparia} var. {\i maritima} Rouy): Branches procumbent with occasional erect or ascending branches from the centre of the plant up to 40 cm; leaves and young twigs densely sericeous. 2n = 46.{\i  Maritime cliffs. Coasts of N.W. Europe}.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    Plants of this subspecies from Britain, Ireland and the Channel Islands retain their characteristics in cultivation. Records from W. France, Germany and Corse require confirmation.
\par

